 author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Yorkshire","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from the county of Yorkshire."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":25,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mathea of Yorkshire was born about 1234, in Huddersfield, Yorkshire, England. She married Thomas I TALBOT of Bashall Eaves, Gov of Clitheroe Castle. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. She died after 1274, in Bashall Eaves, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1234–after 1274":"umbes 1234–pärast 1274","1230–1273":"1230–1273","1260–1310":"1260–1310","1264–Male":"1264–Surnud","1266–Male":"1266–Surnud","1273–1370":"1273